<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18450818-1784">
               <interp inst="t18450818-1784" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18450818"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18450818-1784" type="date" value="18450818"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18450818-1784-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1784-18450818 t18450818-1784-offence-1 t18450818-1784-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1784. <persName id="def1-1784-18450818" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1784-18450818" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1784-18450818" type="age" value="38"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1784-18450818" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1784-18450818" type="given" value="JAMES JESSE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES JESSE TAYLOR</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18450818-1784-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18450818-1784-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18450818-1784-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing 1 bag, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 168lbs. weight of hair, 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18450818-name-1080" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1080" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1080" type="surname" value="MORGAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1080" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18450818-1784-offence-1 t18450818-name-1080"></join>David Morgan</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1081" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1081" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1081" type="surname" value="MORGAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1081" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>DAVID MORGAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a builder, and live in the Old Kent-road. The prisoner was my plasterers' foreman—he was employed at weekly wages—I have some houses building in the Commercial-road, Peckham—he was employed there as foreman—I provided materials for the plastering, and among other things a quantity of hair—on the 17th of May I bought</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184508180185"></xptr>
               <p>2 cwt. of hair of Mr. Harmott—it was placed in Mr. Harmott's cart, and delivered at the buildings—I was present at the time—I paid 19<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for the hair the same day—it was the prisoner's business to receive it—I have the bill of it, which bears the prisoner's handwriting on it, showing that he received it at the building—when payment was required he was to put his name on the bill, and send it as a voucher, and I paid the money—I re-quired the prisoner to take the hair with other materials, to his lodging that he had taken, near the work—I considered it safer there, as several things had been lost from the buildings—some time after that, I saw the hair going towards the prisoner's lodgings—he had my truck under his care, and a labourer with him—on Monday, the 7th of June, I received information from Mr. Forbes, a gentleman living near there, and in conse<lb></lb>quence of that I discovered that a portion of my hair had been taken away—I missed about three-quarters of a cwt., which the prisoner ought to have had in his possession—I went and looked at the hair at Mr. Forbes's, and the sack—I cannot say that they were mine, nor could I swear to the hair or sack that were stolen—I expect the hair that I bought was of that sort and description, but I did not notice it when I purchased it—I did not see the prisoner on the day I went to look for the hair at his house—I saw him on Tuesday morning—I told him I wanted to know what was the reason he had left my work, and I said in the same sentence, "I understand you hare been selling a quantity of hair to Mr. Forbes, and what has become of the hair you had of mine?"—he got up in a hurry, and said be would let me know all about that, and left my house—I did not see him till the officer took him—he said on going out of the door that I had no business to trespass on his place, and he would serve a writ on me for the trespass I had committed in taking things from his lodging—I had taken my own scaffolding and other things from there—I did not see him again for ten days or a fortnight, when the officer brought him—the hair I bought was 2 cwt., and the quantity I authorized him to use about the work was about a quarter of a cwt.—I consider he would have had no occasion to use more than that—there should have been 1 cwt. 3/4 qrs. left.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long had he been in your employ? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Between four and five months—he is a plasterer by trade—he has no shop—I paid him two guineas a week—I gave him into cus<lb></lb>tody about the 21st of July—about a week previous to that I had been served with a writ in an action of trespass—he was employed as my ser-vant, to superintend the plasterers' work at these houses in Commercial-road, Peckham, at one on Blackheath, one at Rye-lane, and one elsewhere—all of these he attended to—I swear that he had not entered into a con<lb></lb>tract with me to plaster these houses at a specific sum for each house—he was employed at Mr. Benbow's about March—he was not employed to do the plasterer's work at that gentleman's—he was then employed at those houses in the Commercial-road—it was at first six carcasses—I will swear I did not agree to pay him 18<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a house for that work—there was no written contract entered into between us in reference to that work, nor with reference to any houses—I directed him to plaster the outside of eighteen houses—he employed the workmen to plaster there, and he paid them their wages, but they were my servants—I authorized him to hire them—two of them came to me for a day and a quarter's wages on the last occasion—after the prisoner left the work, he went to them, and said he should have no more to do with them—they came to me, and I paid them—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184508180186"></xptr>
               <p>have got foremen similar to the prisoner, and they are all authorized to employ men—they all pay them, and the money they want I give them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is it not usual for a plasterer to enter into this kind of contract, to do the work at a certain price, to obtain the goods on the credit of the builder, and to deduct the amount from the contract? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I never heard of it, and nothing of that kind took place with me and the prisoner—Mr. Hook has contracted with a person to do the painting, and this work is a contract on my part—I took the work for 408<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> But I want to know whether any of the plasterers that you employed were ever hired by you, or paid by you, except those two who called on you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, except they came with him, and I gave him the money—I gave him the money for wages once, and I believe once or twice he had money for some beer—I think I gave him 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. about the 6th of April.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you not been served with a notice to bring your books here, and your contracts? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That notice I took no notice of.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You paid the prisoner the sum-total, and he doled it out to the different persons? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1082" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1082" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1082" type="surname" value="SMITHERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1082" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN SMITHERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Robson. I served a notice on the prosecutor's sister, at his house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">DAVID MORGAN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you undertake to swear that no written contract was ever delivered to you by the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have sworn it—I do not know Mr. Franks—I do not know that I have ever seen him—I do not know Mr. Franks (<hi rend="italic">looking at him</hi>)—I only saw him at the office—I never saw him at my counting-house in my life, or at any public-house in company with the prisoner—I swear there are no entries in my books to this effect, that I was to pay the prisoner so much for each house—I never heard of such a thing as the hard core from the mortar being the perqui-site of the builder—if he were to sell any of the remaining materials, I should consider it incorrect—there is hard core from the mortar after build-ing—it is very rarely sold—we are obliged sometimes to pay for taking it away—the prisoner had no authority from me to contract with any other parties to do this work—there were first six houses, and then eighteen, and then four small houses—I did not go to his house and seize on every-thing that I thought was mine—my things were in an open shed in the yard—I took my cart, and his wife pointed out the things that were mine—he did not use his own scaffolding, it was mine—my scaffolding was chiefly taken to my house, but some ropes and small things he took to his place for safety—when I charged him with taking this hair, he did not say It is my hair, you will be served with a writ of trespass"—he never an-swered me about the hair; but when I spoke of hair being sold, he said, "I will let you know all about that"—I did not give him into custody when I spoke to him about the hair, because I was not positive that he had stolen it—I was not as positive about it as I am now—I think I paid him 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. on the 12th of April—I paid him from 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to about 32<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. aweek, all for wages—I cannot tell exactly how many men were employed on that work—I used to go round each day and make a memorandum of how many men were employed—I paid the prisoner 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 28<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 31<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and 18<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., I think, was the last.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> With regard to the hair and other materials, were they all yours and taken to his house for his convenience alone? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi>
               </p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184508180187"></xptr>
               <p>Yes, the ropes and scaffolding—I took all that belonged to me—they were used for this job or any other—I purchased a great many of them for this work, and I authorized the prisoner to hire some articles of a builder—I have got a receipt that I paid the builder for the hire of them—the prisoner hiring the men and I paying him the money for their wages is the usual course of business—I have four other men of different trades who work in the same way.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1083" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1083" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1083" type="surname" value="FORBES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1083" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FORBES</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 3, Camden Villas, Camden<lb></lb>grove, Peck-ham, and am a builder—the prisoner came to me about the 20th of June and entered into a contract for building houses, and I was to find materials for the work—after he had entered into the contract, he said he had more bair than he wanted for Mr. Morgan's work, and asked me to take some—he said he had a two hundred weight bag—on the 27th of June he produced the hair to me, and I agreed to buy it at 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a hundred—I agreed to have one hundred and a half—he said that would be enough for my job—he then drew all the money he could on Saturday night, and left my job—I went to inquire where he was, and gave information to the prosecutor—the hair was all used except about a handful, which the policeman took away—I am sure what he took was some of the same hair that I had from the prisoner—the policeman took possession of the very same bag in which the hair was brought.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What was the contract you entered into? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Seventeen pounds each house—that was for labour only—he represented to me that he had found all the materials for Mr. Morgan's job—I contracted with him to do these houses at so much per house—I had no quarrel with him, but he left my work in a most shameful manner, and took the scaffold-ing away; but I understand it belonged to Mr. Morgan.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1084" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1084" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1084" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1084" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES WHITE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable P</hi> 57.) I produce some hair, and this bag which I brought from Mr. Forbes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1085" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1085" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1085" type="surname" value="HARMOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1085" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY HARMOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. My traveller sold 2 cwt. of hair to Mr. Mor-gan, and I directed a quantity of hair to be packed up from a heap in my warehouse—I have looked at this hair produced by the officer—there is nothing particular about it now, but when I saw it before in the officer's possession, previous to going before the magistrate, there was a small lock of seal-hair amongst it, and by some means it was lost—I took possession of it, but what became of it I cannot tell—in my warehouse in which the hair was which I directed to be packed up for Mr. Morgan, there was a great quantity of seal hair—it is probable that some of it might have got into that sent to Mr. Morgan, and I saw some of it in the hair produced by the officer—it would have been of no use to Mr. Morgan at all—I do not know of any one who sells hair to plasterers having seal hair—this hair produced is similar to what I had in bulk, and sold to Mr. Morgan.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You cannot say whether there was any seal-hair in that sent to Mr. Morgan? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No. I did not see it packed up—the hair *—I sold to Mr. Morgan was received by the prisoner on the premises—I have frequently known plasterers to undertake to do work at so much per house, and for the builder to find the materials, and I have frequently known it done otherwise—the builder generally pays the bills.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know of any case where the builder pays for the materials, and the workman takes the materials to sell to other parties? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—the hair I sent to Mr. Morgan was sent in a similar sack to this.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184508180188"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1086" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1086" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1086" type="surname" value="HARMOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1086" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE HARMOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the son of Mr. Henry Harmott—I did not see the hair packed up for Mr. Morgan—I know this lack to be one of my father's by these knots that I tied at the corner, and this is the sack that went to Mr. Morgan's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you take it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1087" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1087" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1087" type="surname" value="FARNKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1087" type="given" value="JOHN FREDERICK"></interp>JOHN FREDERICK FARNKS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Castle-street, Shoreditch. I have been a builder in that neighbourhood twenty-seven years—I have known the prisoner nearly twenty years, and employed him—he is one of the honestest men I ever employed—I never knew Mr. Morgan till I saw him at a job once or twice—I remember the prisoner working for Mr. Morgan, and I want to the building and measured the work—I was pre<lb></lb>sent when the prisoner gave Mr. Morgan a contract for six houses—he said, "Mr. Morgan, that is the contract for six houses"—Mr. Morgan opened it and said, "It is all right, Taylor, you will hear from me"—I had seen the paper, and read it just before Mr. Morgan came into the public-house—the contents of it were to do the inside plastering of six houses, finding all materials, at 18<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a house—Mr. Morgan read it at the bar, and put it into his pocket—I afterwards gave the prisoner an estimate for plastering the outside of eighteen houses in the Commercial road—I was not present when Mr. Morgan and the prisoner had any conversation with reference to those houses—about April or May I sold the prisoner 2 cwt. of hair—I have sold him hair twenty times—he said he was paying 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for hair, and I said I could sell him some at 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you deal in hair? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, but I have a great deal sometimes—when the prisoner is not employed I give him a job to work for me, and I find the materials—he is not a man of any capital.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where did you buy this job of hair that you sold to the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I reajly cannot tell—I buy of a great many people—I will not tell you exactly where I bought it—it was on a Satur<lb></lb>day evening that I saw the prisoner give the prosecutor a paper—I think it was about the 12th of April—it was at the Nelson, a new public-house, between six and seven o'clock in the evening—it is on the right-hand side of the Kent-road, just through the gate—there were several other persons there, but none that I knew but Taylor—the publican was there, and a person behind the bar, and a little girl, who looked like a Jewess—she might have seen the paper given, and 1 think she did—I had read all the paper—there was not a great deal of it—I took the hair I sold to the pri<lb></lb>soner from a lot which I have—I dare say I have a cwt. and a half there now—I bought it in Cow-lane, just by Smithfield—I did not see any seal hair in that—if I want a lot of huir I send my man and pay for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> In what quantity do you purchase hair? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It depends upon what job I have got—perhaps eight or ten cwt.—I never went on credit in my life for it—I generally deal at Bermondsey or Cow-cross—I built Nicholson's-wharf—the contract for that was some thousands of pounds—I am building now—I have had 200 men at work for me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1088" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1088" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1088" type="surname" value="HEADINGTYON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1088" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD HEADINGTYON</persName>
                  </hi>. I was employed as foreman of the work in the Old Kent-road for Mr. Morgan—I had no conversation with him about the prisoner—he never told me he had contracted with the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450818-name-1089" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1089" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1089" type="surname" value="HOOK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450818-name-1089" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HOOK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a painter. I painted for Mr. Morgan in the com<lb></lb>morcial-road—the prisoner was working there as a plasterer—Mr. Morgan told me and the prisoner that he wanted us to go down to make a contract</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184508180189"></xptr>
               <p>for the work at Peckham—we went, and I contracted for the painting—I believe Taylor gave in a contract for the plastering—he and Morgan were two or three hours together—I heard no conversation between them.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18450818-1784-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
